Once upon a time, a wise old man became tired of his village fortress and decided to leave. everybody was heartbroken; it had been said that few things were as comfortable as he.
He simply passed through the gates with a smile and continued out through the gates. everyone in the village had heard the rumors that the fortress and the man himself were inseparable. They would laugh and tell stories of rides on a barge up his jagged mountain, and feasting to excess at the man’s hearth. This man did not let the fear of the unknown hold back anyone of his villagers that he kept as his own, no, not even a day of mourning when one was left a little unconcuming.
But our fables have not yet had the chance to be told and this tale is a prequel that sets all things up in their order for our world and beyond.

Konrad Zuse (1910-1995) was a German engineer, computer scientist, and inventor, who is considered to be one of the pioneers of computer engineering. He is best known for designing and building the first fully automatic digital computer, the Z3, in the 1940s.
